00:00:01.057 --> 00:00:03.524
Ethical Foundations in Dentistry

00:00:03.524 --> 00:00:04.834
Autonomy

00:00:04.834 --> 00:00:11.091
This principle emphasizes the importance of respecting patients' rights to make informed decisions about their dental care.

00:00:11.091 --> 00:00:14.951
Dentists must educate patients on their treatment options, including risks and

00:00:14.951 --> 00:00:19.278
benefits, allowing them to choose according to their values and preferences.

00:00:19.278 --> 00:00:20.758
Beneficence

00:00:20.758 --> 00:00:26.305
This principle emphasizes the duty of dental professionals to prioritize their patients' best interests.

00:00:26.305 --> 00:00:30.619
It involves offering effective treatment that enhances patient health and well-being.

00:00:30.619 --> 00:00:36.686
Dentists must stay informed about current practices and advancements in order to maintain high care standards.

00:00:36.686 --> 00:00:38.356
Non-Maleficence

00:00:38.356 --> 00:00:45.206
This principle, meaning "do no harm," requires dental practitioners to avoid causing harm or suffering to patients.

00:00:45.206 --> 00:00:51.616
It involves being aware of potential complications and ensuring all procedures are necessary and performed carefully.

00:00:51.616 --> 00:00:52.825
Justice

00:00:52.825 --> 00:01:01.700
This principle emphasizes fairness in dental care, ensuring all patients receive equitable treatment, regardless of background or socioeconomic status.

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:07.150
Dentists should work to eliminate biases and provide access to quality services for everyone.

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:08.969
Confidentiality

00:01:08.969 --> 00:01:14.090
Protecting patient information is essential for maintaining trust between patients and dentists.

00:01:14.090 --> 00:01:19.792
Dental professionals must safeguard personal health information and only share it with authorized individuals.

00:01:19.792 --> 00:01:24.278
Informed consent is necessary before disclosing any patient information.

00:01:24.278 --> 00:01:32.518
These ethical foundations guide dental practitioners in fostering trust, ensuring patient safety, and providing high-quality care in their practice.
